<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Symposium Delivers Simple Message: Job Opportunities Almost Limitless With a Science Degree</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 11, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004105bd60439010c0c76ce2f0062e4"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Making students aware of the variety of job opportunities available today with a science degree was the goal of the first Career Opportunities in Biomedical Sciences symposium held at the University of Central Florida last week. </p><p /><p>The molecular biology and microbiology departments as well as the Burnett Honors College sponsored the daylong event held at the Student Union on Sept. 7. About 25 students attended getting tips on everything from the variety of jobs available to how to prepare for admission into a medical school. </p><p /><p>Students can have up to three job offers before you finish your microbiology or molecular biology degree at UCF, said Dorilyn Hitchcock, the director of the Medical Laboratory Science Program. </p><p /><p>From medical techs to X-ray technicians, there are lots of jobs, Hitchcock said, although pay isnÂ’t as great as that of a doctor. However, as the population continues to age and there are more medical needs, she predicts salaries will also increase. </p><p /><p>And UCF will be in a position to help fill those jobs with a variety of medical related degrees being offered. This past year the state authorized the university to open a medical school. UCF has hired a firm to find a dean and the process for accreditation is underway. The school is scheduled to open in Lake Nona in the fall of 2009. </p><p>Beyond doctors and nurses, there are many other jobs, said Kenneth Teter, an assistant professor in molecular biology and microbiology. He came up with the idea for the symposium last year when he was giving a lecture to students. </p><p /><p>Â“I was talking about patenting your work and patent law,Â” Teter said. Â“The look on my students faces, they had no idea. ThereÂ’s more you can do with a degree, but you need to tailor it to your future goals.Â” </p><p /><p>And that future can be in a science lab, with patients, in the business world or even in law, depending on what you want to do. One professor talked about an attorney with whom he worked that had a degree in environmental science and microbiology. He helped the professor with a patent to protect his intellectual property. </p><p /><p>Â“Do you like patient contact or collecting data?,Â” Hitchcock said. Â“Whatever the answer, thereÂ’s a job for you.Â” </p><p /><p>The 18 speakers covered a range of career options from becoming doctors and chemists in industry to practicing law and helping creating public policy when it comes to biomedical technology. </p><p /><p>Russell Higbee, a former professor at Purdue University turned biotechnology entrepreneur, spoke about Vax Design. The Orlando-based biotech company is engineering a human immune system to help get pharmaceuticals to market sooner. The company has created an artificial Lymph node and simulated the immune system outside the body. He has several degrees, including a bachelorÂ’s in anatomy, a veterinary degree and a doctorate in cell biology. </p><p /><p>Higbee spoke about the exciting options available to students who are interested in bioengineering. He kept updating his education and capitalized on opportunities when he saw them. </p><p /><p>He said the world of employment is vast for anyone who graduates with a science degree </p><p /><p /><p><span ar-sa?="" mso-bidi-language:="" en-us;="" mso-fareast-language:="" mso-ansi-language:="" roman?;="" new="" ?times="" mso-fareast-font-family:="" times="">Â“You have to be motivated and think outside the box,&quot; he said.</span> </p>
		
	
